<TITLE> Dhaka, Delhi talk sea borders after 28 years </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 14 (bdnews24.com)Bangladesh and India restart maritime border talks on Monday, after almost three decades, with a view to demarcating sea boundaries between the two countries. "These technical level talks are talking place after 28 years," foreign adviser Iftekhar Ahmed Chowdhury told reporters Sunday at his foreign ministry office. "We believe today both governments are deeply committed to strengthening their relations through resolution of all outstanding issues." A 7-member Indian delegation, led by rear admiral BR Rao, arrived on a Jet Airways flight Sunday afternoon, Zia International Airport immigration officer in-charge told bdnews24.com. Additional foreign secretary MAK Mahmood will lead the Bangladesh side in the three-day conference. According to the United Nations Convention on Law of the Sea (UNCLOS), Bangladesh must demarcate her sea boundaries by 2011, and India by 2009. Bangladesh has had disputes over sea boundary demarcations with India and Myanmar. Bangladesh has also initiated maritime border talks with Myanmar. bdn
